title: Can you solve the prisoner hat riddle?

aws-transcripts.transcript: you and nine other individuals have been captured by super intelligent alien overlords. Theo. Aliens think humans look quite tasty, but their civilization for bids, eating highly logical and cooperative beings. Unfortunately, they're not sure whether you qualify. So they decided to give you all a test through its universal translator. The alien guarding you tells you the following you will be placed in a single file line facing forward in size order so that each of you can see everyone lined up ahead of you. You will not be able to look behind you or step out of line. Each of you will have either a black or a white hat on your head assigned randomly, and I won't tell you how many of each color there are. When I say to begin, each of you must guess the color of your hat, starting with the person in the back and moving up the line. And don't even try saying words other than black or white or signaling some other way like intonation or volume. You all be eaten immediately. If at least nine of you guessed correctly you'll all be spared. You have front of minutes to discuss Internet for the pretty way of saying your hats again, can you think of a strategy guaranteed to save everyone? The key is that the person at the back of the line who can see everyone else's hats can use the words black or white to communicate some coded information. So what meaning can be assigned to those words that will allow everyone else to deduce their hat colors? It can't be the total number of black or white hats. There are more than two possible values. But what does have two possible values is that number's parody. That is, whether it's odd or even so. The solution is to agree that whoever goes first will, for example, say Black if he sees an odd number of black hats and white if he sees an even number of black cats, let's see how it would play out if the hats were distributed like this. The tallest captive sees three black hats in front of him, so he says black, telling everyone else he sees an odd number of black hats. He gets his own hat color wrong, but that's okay, since you're collectively allowed tohave one wrong answer prisoner to also sees an odd number of black hats, so she knows her is is white and answers correctly. Prisoner three sees an even number of black hats, so he knows that Hiss must be one of the black hats The 1st 2 prisoners saw. Prisoner Four hears that and knows that she should be looking for an even number of black hats since one was behind her. But she only sees one. So she deduce, is that her hat is also black. Prisoners five through nine are each looking for an odd number of black hats, which they see, so they figure out that their hats are white. Now it all comes down to you at the front of the line. If the ninth prisoner saw an odd number of black hats, that can only mean one thing. You'll find that this strategy works for any possible arrangement of the hats. The first prisoner has a 50% chance of giving a wrong answer about his own hat, but the parody information he conveys allows everyone else thio. Guess there's with absolute certainty. Each begins by expecting to see an odd or even number of hats of the specified color if what they count doesn't match, that means there own hat is that color. And every time this happens, the next person in line will switch the parody they expect to see. So that's it. You're free to go. It looks like these aliens will have to go hungry or find some less logical organisms to abduct.
